identificationModule.briefTitle: Trial of JYB1904 in Chronic Spontaneous Urticaria.
identificationModule.officialTitle: A Multicenter, Randomized, Double-blind, Parallel-group, Active-controlled Phase II Clinical Study to Evaluate the Efficacy, Safety and Tolerability of JYB1904 Injection in Adult Patients with Chronic Spontaneous Urticaria Inadequately Controlled by H1 Antihistamines

descriptionModule.briefSummary: This Phase II Trial is Meant to Evaluate the Efficacy, Safety and Tolerability of JYB1904 Injection in Patients With Chronic Spontaneous Urticaria.

interventions.name: JYB1904
interventions.description: Participants will receive JYB1904 at week0 and receive placebo at week4,8,12

interventions.name: JYB1904
interventions.description: Participants will receive JYB1904 at week0,8 and receive placebo at week4,12

interventions.name: Omalizumab
interventions.description: Participants will receive Omalizumab every 4 weeks for 12 weeks

primaryOutcomes.measure: Urticaria activity score used for 7 consecutive days(UAS7)
primaryOutcomes.description: Change from baseline in urticaria activity score used for 7 consecutive days (UAS7) at weeks 8, 12, and 16.Score 0-42, UAS7=0 for complete remission

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Urticaria activity score used for 7 consecutive days(UAS7)
secondaryOutcomes.description: Change from baseline in UAS7 at weeks 4, 24 and 32.Score 0-42, UAS7=0 for complete remission

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Itch severity score used for 7 consecutive days(ISS7)
secondaryOutcomes.description: Change from baseline in itch severity score used for 7 consecutive days(ISS7) at weeks 4, 8, 12, 16, 24 and 32.Score 0-21, ISS7=0 for complete remission of itch

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Hive severity score used for 7 consecutive days (HSS7)
secondaryOutcomes.description: Change from baseline in hive severity score used for 7 consecutive days(HSS7) at weeks 4, 8, 12, 16, 24, 32.Score 0-21, HSS7=0 for complete remission of hives

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Angioedema activity score used for 7 consecutive days(AAS7)
secondaryOutcomes.description: Change from baseline in angioedema activity score used for 7 consecutive days(AAS7) at weeks 4, 8, 12, 16, 24, 32.Score 0-105, higher scores mean a worse outcome

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Urticaria activity score used for 7 consecutive days(UAS7)
secondaryOutcomes.description: Proportion of subjects with UAS7=0 at weeks 4, 8, 12, 16, 24, 32.Score 0-42, UAS7=0 for complete remission
Change from baseline in Dermatological Life Quality Index (DLQI) at weeks 4, 8, 12, 16, 24 and 32.Score 0-30, higher scores mean a worse outcome
Adverse events (AEs) and serious adverse events (SAEs)

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Trends in serum total immunoglobulin E(IgE)
secondaryOutcomes.description: Serum total IgE levels at weeks 4, 8, 12, 16, 24 and 32

secondaryOutcomes.measure: Positive detection rate of anti-drug antibody (ADA)
secondaryOutcomes.description: ADA positive detection rate at 32 weeks

eligibilityModule.eligibilityCriteria:
Inclusion Criteria:

* Male or female adult subjects (≥18 years of age).
* Diagnosis of Chronic Spontaneous Urticaria(CSU) ≥ 3 months prior to Screening Visit 1 and previously inadequately controlled with a second-generation H1 antihistamine.
* Itching and hives lasting ≥ 6 weeks prior to Screening Visit 1.
* Have a UAS7 (range 0 - 42) ≥ 16, an ISS7 (range 0 - 21) ≥ 6, and an HSS7 (range 0 - 21) ≥ 6 within 7 days prior to randomization.

Exclusion Criteria:

* Induced urticaria with a defined trigger, including artificial urticaria (cutaneous scratches), cold-contact, heat-contact, solar, pressure, delayed-pressure, water-source, cholinergic, or contact urticaria
* Any other dermatological condition with chronic itching, such as atopic dermatitis, herpetic pemphigoid, herpetic dermatitis, senile itching, or psoriasis, which in the opinion of the investigator may affect the study assessment and study results
* Other conditions with symptoms of urticaria or angioedema, including but not limited to urticarial vasculitis, pigmented urticaria, erythema multiforme, mastocytosis, hereditary urticaria, or acquired/drug-induced urticaria.
* Previous allergic reaction or poor efficacy with omalizumab.
* Contraindication or hypersensitivity to antihistamines (e.g., fexofenadine, loratadine, desloratadine, cetirizine, levocetirizine, rupatadine, bilastine) or any of the ingredients.
